1
00:00:01,566 --> 00:00:03,655
Last day of training.

2
00:00:03,699 --> 00:00:05,048
Last day of Tim barking orders.

3
00:00:05,092 --> 00:00:07,268
Last day that they can fire us
at a moment's notice.

4
00:00:07,311 --> 00:00:10,358
Last day of them recording
every flaw for posterity.

5
00:00:10,401 --> 00:00:12,012
It's kind of bittersweet.

6
00:00:12,055 --> 00:00:13,361
Nope. Just sweet.

7
00:00:13,404 --> 00:00:15,058
Sorry. Sorry.

8
00:00:15,102 --> 00:00:16,581
Guys, stop apologizing.

9
00:00:16,625 --> 00:00:18,670
You guys have finally made it,

10
00:00:18,714 --> 00:00:19,671
and I will be right behind you.

11
00:00:19,715 --> 00:00:21,108
Look, the extra month
will fly by.

12
00:00:21,151 --> 00:00:22,370
You know it.

13
00:00:22,413 --> 00:00:24,589
Now, is Tim gonna do
anything special

14
00:00:24,633 --> 00:00:26,896
to memorialize
your last shift together?

15
00:00:26,939 --> 00:00:28,071
Not knowingly.

16
00:00:28,115 --> 00:00:29,072
You know, when you move on

17
00:00:29,116 --> 00:00:31,031
from an important relationship,

18
00:00:31,074 --> 00:00:34,860
there are steps you should take
to ensure a healthy parting.

19
00:00:34,904 --> 00:00:37,602
We are going to work through
every single one of them.

20
00:00:37,646 --> 00:00:39,517
Uh, how, if he doesn't know
you're doing it?

21
00:00:39,561 --> 00:00:41,476
Trickery. Bye.

22
00:00:41,519 --> 00:00:44,087
That's... Yeah.

23
00:00:44,131 --> 00:00:45,175
Who are <i>you</i> gonna ride with
today?

24
00:00:45,219 --> 00:00:46,611
No idea.

25
00:00:46,655 --> 00:00:48,961
Grey's busy, and Smitty's
getting a back tattoo.

26
00:00:49,005 --> 00:00:50,789
That's -- Yeah. Don't ask.

27
00:00:50,833 --> 00:00:52,922
So, we are out of TOs,
and I'm guessing

28
00:00:52,965 --> 00:00:54,489
I'm finishing my rookie year
at the front desk.

29
00:00:54,532 --> 00:00:55,664
Huh. Boot.

30
00:00:57,927 --> 00:00:59,102
Where's our gear?

31
00:00:59,146 --> 00:01:01,148
Wait, what?

32
00:01:01,191 --> 00:01:03,019
We started this journey
together.

33
00:01:03,063 --> 00:01:04,325
I think we should end it
that way.

34
00:01:04,368 --> 00:01:05,587
Don't you?

35
00:01:05,630 --> 00:01:06,588
Yeah.

36
00:01:06,631 --> 00:01:08,155
Then let's go.

37
00:01:12,115 --> 00:01:13,421
I thought we were tight.

38
00:01:13,464 --> 00:01:14,509
You did?

39
00:01:14,552 --> 00:01:15,553
Um, we are.

40
00:01:15,597 --> 00:01:17,468
That's -- I mean, why? What?

41
00:01:17,512 --> 00:01:19,122
You told your ethics professor

42
00:01:19,166 --> 00:01:20,732
she should come for
a ride along?

43
00:01:20,776 --> 00:01:21,733
No.

44
00:01:21,777 --> 00:01:22,778
Mm. We -- No.

45
00:01:22,821 --> 00:01:24,214
We didn't even, uh, discuss it,

46
00:01:24,258 --> 00:01:25,868
but I-I need to pass this class,

47
00:01:25,911 --> 00:01:29,045
so it's super important
she doesn't get shot today.

48
00:01:29,089 --> 00:01:30,394
No promises.

49
00:01:30,438 --> 00:01:31,961
You ride with me, you ride
the roller coaster.

50
00:01:32,004 --> 00:01:33,528
Okay, Nyla, I know that --

51
00:01:33,571 --> 00:01:35,312
- Hi. Good morning.
- Good morning.

52
00:01:35,356 --> 00:01:37,401
Uh, Professor Ryan, this is
Detective Nyla Harper,

53
00:01:37,445 --> 00:01:38,620
my training officer.

54
00:01:38,663 --> 00:01:39,621
I'm told you're gonna be going

55
00:01:39,664 --> 00:01:41,013
on a ride along with us today.

56
00:01:41,057 --> 00:01:42,711
I hope that's okay.

57
00:01:42,754 --> 00:01:45,017
I didn't want to put you in an
awkward position by asking you,

58
00:01:45,061 --> 00:01:46,932
but your watch commander said
that you'd feel cheated

59
00:01:46,976 --> 00:01:48,238
if I didn't ride with you, so...

60
00:01:48,282 --> 00:01:50,066
And he was right.

61
00:01:51,198 --> 00:01:52,155
- Uh, shall we?
- Mm.

62
00:01:52,199 --> 00:01:54,331
Okay.

63
00:01:54,375 --> 00:01:56,159
So, you, uh,
sign all the paperwork

64
00:01:56,203 --> 00:01:57,508
that says that we are not liable

65
00:01:57,552 --> 00:01:59,293
if you are maimed or killed?

66
00:01:59,336 --> 00:02:00,946
I did. It seemed
a bit excessive.

67
00:02:00,990 --> 00:02:02,339
Mm. No, it's not.

68
00:02:02,383 --> 00:02:04,167
I mean, we will try our best
to protect you,

69
00:02:04,211 --> 00:02:06,952
but we cannot guarantee
your safety.

70
00:02:06,996 --> 00:02:10,173
You will be exposed to all
the same dangers that we are.

71
00:02:10,217 --> 00:02:13,611
Well, more farmers die yearly
than cops do.

72
00:02:13,655 --> 00:02:15,091
I didn't have to sign
a liability waiver

73
00:02:15,135 --> 00:02:16,527
to go apple picking.

74
00:02:16,571 --> 00:02:18,094
That's because you weren't
picking them

75
00:02:18,138 --> 00:02:19,139
out of a wood chipper.

76
00:02:19,182 --> 00:02:20,401
Uh, hey,

77
00:02:20,444 --> 00:02:21,924
have you ever seen
a body camera up close?

78
00:02:21,967 --> 00:02:23,055
No.

79
00:02:23,099 --> 00:02:24,405
Well, they're always running,

80
00:02:24,448 --> 00:02:26,537
uh, until we actually need them.

81
00:02:26,581 --> 00:02:27,886
We switch them on,
then they start recording,

82
00:02:27,930 --> 00:02:29,279
and they go back two minutes

83
00:02:29,323 --> 00:02:30,672
so we can catch any of that
last-minute action.

84
00:02:30,715 --> 00:02:32,804
Oh, yet they're always broken

85
00:02:32,848 --> 00:02:34,850
whenever the cops
cross the line.

86
00:02:34,893 --> 00:02:36,895
You'd be surprised
how many police officers

87
00:02:36,939 --> 00:02:39,028
actually <i>want a body camera.</i>

88
00:02:39,071 --> 00:02:40,334
Oh. That way,

89
00:02:40,377 --> 00:02:42,205
it makes it easier to
disprove complaints.

90
00:02:42,249 --> 00:02:44,773
Okay, then you will not mind

91
00:02:44,816 --> 00:02:47,297
if I record
the ride along myself --

92
00:02:47,341 --> 00:02:48,298
as research tool.

93
00:02:48,342 --> 00:02:49,169
No problem.

94
00:02:52,084 --> 00:02:53,912
Just as long as you turn it off

95
00:02:53,956 --> 00:02:56,437
when we hit the strip club
for the lunch buffet.

96
00:02:59,266 --> 00:03:00,528
She's kidding.

97
00:03:00,571 --> 00:03:02,704
That buffet is terrible
at that strip club.

98
00:03:02,747 --> 00:03:04,314
♪ Whoa, oh, oh, oh Ready to go?

99
00:03:04,358 --> 00:03:06,447
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh

100
00:03:06,490 --> 00:03:11,234
♪ I'm gonna win for you
like I know you want me to do ♪

101
00:03:12,540 --> 00:03:13,976
You got yours on? Yeah.

102
00:03:14,019 --> 00:03:15,630
Alright.

103
00:03:15,673 --> 00:03:17,240
It's our last shift together.

104
00:03:17,284 --> 00:03:18,459
It's crazy, huh?

105
00:03:18,502 --> 00:03:19,982
Not really.

106
00:03:20,025 --> 00:03:21,331
Come on.

107
00:03:21,375 --> 00:03:22,593
I mean, we've been
riding shoulder to shoulder

108
00:03:22,637 --> 00:03:24,116
for over a year now.

109
00:03:24,160 --> 00:03:26,075
And soon, there'll be a new
rookie sitting in that seat,

110
00:03:26,118 --> 00:03:28,643
annoying the crap out of me
for 12 hours a day.

111
00:03:28,686 --> 00:03:31,559
So, you're not gonna
miss riding with me at all?

112
00:03:31,602 --> 00:03:33,256
It's a job, not happy hour.

113
00:03:33,300 --> 00:03:35,563
Mm. Denial. Check.

114
00:03:36,868 --> 00:03:38,130
What? Hmm?

115
00:03:38,174 --> 00:03:39,262
Nothing.

116
00:03:46,965 --> 00:03:49,664
So, you teach full time?

117
00:03:49,707 --> 00:03:52,188
No. Just nights and weekends.

118
00:03:52,232 --> 00:03:54,756
My day job is
civil rights litigation.

119
00:03:54,799 --> 00:03:56,584
And then there's lecturing,
the writing,

120
00:03:56,627 --> 00:03:57,933
the cable news hits.

121
00:03:57,976 --> 00:03:58,934
When do you sleep?

122
00:03:58,977 --> 00:04:00,457
Sleep? What's that?

123
00:04:00,501 --> 00:04:02,242
Oh, is that what you were doing
in my class on Monday?

124
00:04:02,285 --> 00:04:04,156
What?

125
00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:05,201
No. Uh, no.

126
00:04:05,245 --> 00:04:06,289
Sometimes, I just --
I hold a blink

127
00:04:06,333 --> 00:04:08,117
for a really long time.

128
00:04:08,160 --> 00:04:09,858
You sure lying to your teacher
is the way to go here?

129
00:04:09,901 --> 00:04:10,989
Actually, now that
I hear it out loud,

130
00:04:11,033 --> 00:04:12,164
I'd like to revise my answer.

131
00:04:12,208 --> 00:04:14,036
Yeah. Uh-huh.

132
00:04:14,079 --> 00:04:16,038
So, uh, given how busy you are,

133
00:04:16,081 --> 00:04:18,214
why take the time
for a ride along?

134
00:04:18,258 --> 00:04:21,217
Well, I'm finishing up a book
on the future of policing.

135
00:04:21,261 --> 00:04:24,176
Hey, what would you say is
the, uh, biggest challenge

136
00:04:24,220 --> 00:04:26,483
you face day to day?

137
00:04:26,527 --> 00:04:28,616
Finding a safe bathroom.

138
00:04:28,659 --> 00:04:30,095
Uh, that is -- that is true.

139
00:04:30,139 --> 00:04:32,359
I mean, we can't use a
stall bathroom for safety reasons.

140
00:04:32,402 --> 00:04:34,099
The door has to go
floor to ceiling.

141
00:04:34,143 --> 00:04:36,145
And the location of
the bathroom, also very important,

142
00:04:36,188 --> 00:04:38,321
so that not a lot of people can
see us entering and leaving.

143
00:04:39,627 --> 00:04:40,976
<i>7-Adam-15,</i>

144
00:04:41,019 --> 00:04:44,109
<i>residential burglary alarm,
1330 Monrovia.</i>

145
00:04:44,153 --> 00:04:46,111
Hundred bucks it's
an accidental trigger.

146
00:04:46,155 --> 00:04:47,461
That is a hard pass.

147
00:04:47,504 --> 00:04:49,376
She's -- She's kidding.

148
00:04:49,419 --> 00:04:51,116
No. No way we'd blow off
a service call.

149
00:04:52,161 --> 00:04:53,858
Copy. Responding.

150
00:04:55,077 --> 00:04:56,426
Do you see yourself
as my mentor?

151
00:04:57,601 --> 00:04:59,690
No. I'm your TO.

152
00:04:59,734 --> 00:05:02,214
It's my job to make sure you're
not dangerously incompetent

153
00:05:02,258 --> 00:05:05,087
when you hit the streets
without supervision tomorrow.

154
00:05:05,130 --> 00:05:06,262
You know, when I was a rookie,

155
00:05:06,306 --> 00:05:07,350
I couldn't wait
to get off probation.

156
00:05:07,394 --> 00:05:09,178
Oh, I am excited.

157
00:05:09,221 --> 00:05:10,832
Believe me.

158
00:05:10,875 --> 00:05:14,096
But I also know the importance of
acknowledging your loss

159
00:05:14,139 --> 00:05:16,185
when going through something like this.

160
00:05:16,228 --> 00:05:17,491
"Acknowledging your loss"?

161
00:05:17,534 --> 00:05:18,970
Hmm.

162
00:05:19,014 --> 00:05:21,451
What is this, some
"Intro to Psych" closure BS?

163
00:05:21,495 --> 00:05:23,279
It's not BS.

164
00:05:23,323 --> 00:05:25,237
It's a widely used
psychological model

165
00:05:25,281 --> 00:05:27,805
to help people cope
with the end of a relationship.

166
00:05:27,849 --> 00:05:29,329
Relationship?

167
00:05:29,372 --> 00:05:31,548
Partnership. Mentorship.

168
00:05:31,592 --> 00:05:32,767
Whatever you want to call it.

169
00:05:32,810 --> 00:05:34,246
Look, I don't want to
call it anything.

170
00:05:34,290 --> 00:05:36,074
It's not like you won't see me
tomorrow at the station.

171
00:05:36,118 --> 00:05:37,859
You know, what's there
to talk about?

172
00:05:37,902 --> 00:05:39,339
A lot.

173
00:05:39,382 --> 00:05:41,253
I have a list.

174
00:05:41,297 --> 00:05:42,603
So... A list?

175
00:05:44,909 --> 00:05:47,608
You know, littering is a $250 fine.

176
00:05:47,651 --> 00:05:50,001
Worth it.

177
00:05:50,045 --> 00:05:51,394
What are you smiling about?

178
00:05:51,438 --> 00:05:54,397
Well, we were at denial,

179
00:05:54,441 --> 00:05:57,444
but now we have moved to anger.

180
00:05:57,487 --> 00:05:58,880
That's more progress.

181
00:06:03,232 --> 00:06:04,189
Thank you.

182
00:06:06,366 --> 00:06:07,541
Gets me out of the office.

183
00:06:07,584 --> 00:06:09,238
I mean, not just for today.

184
00:06:09,281 --> 00:06:10,631
I mean, you could have
bounced me from the program

185
00:06:10,674 --> 00:06:12,807
after that first day.

186
00:06:12,850 --> 00:06:14,243
I owe you my career.

187
00:06:14,286 --> 00:06:15,897
♪ I confess,
don't hate the playa... ♪

188
00:06:15,940 --> 00:06:17,812
- I'd settle for a sandwich.
- We're near Phillipe's.

189
00:06:17,855 --> 00:06:19,422
But you just had breakfast.

190
00:06:19,466 --> 00:06:20,902
You questioning
the pregnant lady?

191
00:06:20,945 --> 00:06:22,294
No, ma'am. No, ma'am.

192
00:06:22,338 --> 00:06:23,600
What?

193
00:06:24,819 --> 00:06:26,298
You're gonna be a mom.

194
00:06:27,038 --> 00:06:29,258
And?

195
00:06:29,301 --> 00:06:30,912
I don't know. I mean...

196
00:06:30,955 --> 00:06:34,002
a lot's happened since
we started out together.

197
00:06:34,045 --> 00:06:36,134
I knew my TO would be
important to my career,

198
00:06:36,178 --> 00:06:38,441
but ...don't know.

199
00:06:38,485 --> 00:06:40,138
I didn't realize how important
you'd be to my life.

200
00:06:40,182 --> 00:06:41,792
♪ They might shine, but
when they lights go out... ♪

201
00:06:41,836 --> 00:06:44,229
- Lay off the sappy stuff.
- I'm nauseous enough as it is.

202
00:06:47,929 --> 00:06:48,799
Have you read my work?

203
00:06:49,974 --> 00:06:51,454
I have.

204
00:06:51,498 --> 00:06:52,977
I actually follow you
on social media.

205
00:06:53,021 --> 00:06:54,979
Oh. And?

206
00:06:55,023 --> 00:06:58,069
I'd make a lot of the reforms
you're pushing for,

207
00:06:58,113 --> 00:07:00,332
but some just aren't
based in reality.

208
00:07:00,376 --> 00:07:02,726
Well, maybe not your reality.

209
00:07:02,770 --> 00:07:04,685
Look, either you want
my opinion or you don't.

210
00:07:04,728 --> 00:07:07,470
If you are just here to confirm
your own point of view,

211
00:07:07,514 --> 00:07:08,819
then I-I will stop engaging.

212
00:07:08,863 --> 00:07:10,168
No, no, no, no.
That's not what I'm looking for.

213
00:07:10,212 --> 00:07:12,475
I-I'm just used to cops taking my head off

214
00:07:12,519 --> 00:07:14,434
any time I suggest changing the status quo.

215
00:07:14,477 --> 00:07:15,957
So...
Well, you would be
surprised

216
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,089
how many cops actually know
the system has to change,

217
00:07:18,133 --> 00:07:20,004
but just feel powerless
to make it happen.

218
00:07:20,048 --> 00:07:21,441
Hmm.

219
00:07:23,443 --> 00:07:25,140
Homeowner set off the alarm
accidentally.

220
00:07:25,183 --> 00:07:26,097
Hundred bucks.

221
00:07:26,141 --> 00:07:27,359
Just put it on my tab.

222
00:07:27,403 --> 00:07:29,187
So, you two getting along? Huh?

223
00:07:29,231 --> 00:07:30,232
My two teachers?

224
00:07:30,275 --> 00:07:31,363
Mm. Yeah.

225
00:07:31,407 --> 00:07:32,756
We're bonding
by making fun of you.

226
00:07:32,800 --> 00:07:34,802
- Oh. Outstanding.
- Let me get in on that.

227
00:07:34,845 --> 00:07:35,585
Have you noticed
how much I've been

228
00:07:35,629 --> 00:07:37,457
saying "like" lately?

229
00:07:39,763 --> 00:07:40,851
Child abduction.

230
00:07:40,895 --> 00:07:42,940
Suspect is driving a gold Tacoma truck.

231
00:07:42,984 --> 00:07:44,246
Plate number

232
00:07:44,289 --> 00:07:47,162
2-Queen-Robert-Ida-4-4-5.

233
00:07:47,205 --> 00:07:48,163
Victim was kidnapped from...

234
00:07:48,206 --> 00:07:49,730
City of Angels Hospital.

235
00:07:49,773 --> 00:07:51,209
How old?

236
00:07:51,253 --> 00:07:53,385
Uh... five hours.

237
00:07:57,477 --> 00:07:58,434
Here we go.

238
00:08:03,570 --> 00:08:04,571
Air Three is lifting now.

239
00:08:04,614 --> 00:08:05,746
I'm 10-9-7.

240
00:08:05,789 --> 00:08:08,836
Searching for the suspect vehicle.

241
00:08:08,879 --> 00:08:11,795
Uh, newborn baby girl went
missing 20 minutes ago.

242
00:08:11,839 --> 00:08:13,971
The hospital is going
over the surveillance footage.

243
00:08:14,015 --> 00:08:15,843
Wait, don't all babies
get LoJack these days?

244
00:08:15,886 --> 00:08:18,106
Yeah, it was found
in the elevator, cut off.

245
00:08:18,149 --> 00:08:19,760
Who owns the Tacoma?

246
00:08:19,803 --> 00:08:22,240
Uh, that would be the
father -- Jared Young.

247
00:08:22,284 --> 00:08:23,981
Looks like they're going through
a messy divorce.

248
00:08:24,025 --> 00:08:26,244
He was visiting the
hospital earlier that day,

249
00:08:26,288 --> 00:08:27,768
but security had him leave.

250
00:08:27,811 --> 00:08:29,247
There may have been some kind of threat.

251
00:08:29,291 --> 00:08:31,032
So, what, he went back in
and he just took the baby?

252
00:08:31,075 --> 00:08:32,903
Jared's got quite an
extensive criminal history here.

253
00:08:32,947 --> 00:08:34,818
Lot of narcos --uh, narco possession,

254
00:08:34,862 --> 00:08:37,125
possession to sell, under the influence.

255
00:08:37,168 --> 00:08:38,822
Mm, just the guy you want
taking care of your newborn.

256
00:08:38,866 --> 00:08:40,171
Well, we got the whole
city looking for him.

257
00:08:40,215 --> 00:08:41,172
He won't get far.

258
00:08:41,216 --> 00:08:43,566
So, this baby that the, uh,

259
00:08:43,610 --> 00:08:45,089
whole city is mobilized
to find --

260
00:08:45,133 --> 00:08:46,526
is she by any chance white?

261
00:08:48,005 --> 00:08:49,529
We issue plenty of Amber Alerts

262
00:08:49,572 --> 00:08:50,965
for children of color, as well.

263
00:08:52,619 --> 00:08:53,707
Do you have a kid?

264
00:08:53,750 --> 00:08:55,404
Daughter.

265
00:08:55,447 --> 00:08:56,753
And, uh, you're sure
your daughter

266
00:08:56,797 --> 00:08:58,581
would get the same attention
as his son?

267
00:08:59,451 --> 00:09:01,105
From the media? No.

268
00:09:01,149 --> 00:09:05,109
But out here, we --
we look just as hard.

269
00:09:05,153 --> 00:09:06,850
Mrs. Young, this is Detective Lopez.

270
00:09:06,894 --> 00:09:08,765
I'm out here searching for your baby.

271
00:09:08,809 --> 00:09:09,984
<i>You have to find her.</i>

272
00:09:10,027 --> 00:09:11,246
Yes, ma'am, we're doing everything we can,

273
00:09:11,289 --> 00:09:12,726
but I need your help.

274
00:09:12,769 --> 00:09:14,554
Is there any place your
husband might take her?

275
00:09:14,597 --> 00:09:15,729
<i>He lives in Bell Gardens.</i>

276
00:09:15,772 --> 00:09:17,078
Yes, ma'am.

277
00:09:17,121 --> 00:09:18,645
We have officers on the
way to his apartment now,

278
00:09:18,688 --> 00:09:21,517
but if he's not there,
where would he be?

279
00:09:21,561 --> 00:09:24,346
<i>Out buying drugs,
if he has any money.</i>

280
00:09:24,389 --> 00:09:25,826
And if he's not?

281
00:09:25,869 --> 00:09:27,958
<i>Jared will do anything
to get a fix,</i>

282
00:09:28,002 --> 00:09:30,526
<i>including selling our baby.</i>

283
00:09:34,225 --> 00:09:35,662
Gold pickup, two blocks up.

284
00:09:40,405 --> 00:09:42,582
Negative. Texas plates.

285
00:09:43,974 --> 00:09:45,193
Five hours old.

286
00:09:45,236 --> 00:09:46,760
That poor mother must
be going out of her mind.

287
00:09:48,805 --> 00:09:49,850
Let me guess --

288
00:09:49,893 --> 00:09:51,329
you think if the parents
had properly

289
00:09:51,373 --> 00:09:52,809
worked through their separation,

290
00:09:52,853 --> 00:09:54,245
this whole thing
could have been avoided?

291
00:09:54,289 --> 00:09:58,032
No. Mom needs to get as
far away from him as possible.

292
00:09:58,075 --> 00:10:00,338
But I do think that having easier access

293
00:10:00,382 --> 00:10:01,775
to counseling and mental health resources

294
00:10:01,818 --> 00:10:03,428
could prevent situations like this.

295
00:10:03,472 --> 00:10:05,692
Sure. But most guys
still wouldn't go.

296
00:10:05,735 --> 00:10:07,302
Yeah, because we stigmatize mental health,

297
00:10:07,345 --> 00:10:10,000
treat it as less
important than physical health.

298
00:10:10,044 --> 00:10:11,828
It's ridiculous that they
teach sex ed in schools,

299
00:10:11,872 --> 00:10:14,352
but not how to be
in a relationship.

300
00:10:14,396 --> 00:10:15,919
I wish someone taught me
how to be in this one.

301
00:10:15,963 --> 00:10:17,486
Oh, so we <i>are in a relationship.</i>

302
00:10:19,706 --> 00:10:21,577
So, what's the focus of your book?

303
00:10:21,621 --> 00:10:23,666
Uh, reinventing policing --

304
00:10:23,710 --> 00:10:25,276
with a more limited mandate.

305
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:26,887
Amen to that.

306
00:10:26,930 --> 00:10:29,019
You agree with taking
resources away from police?

307
00:10:29,063 --> 00:10:31,674
If it lessens our load,
then yes, absolutely.

308
00:10:31,718 --> 00:10:33,545
Yeah, we complain about it all the time.

309
00:10:33,589 --> 00:10:35,765
Police have become the
catch-all for the city's problems.

310
00:10:35,809 --> 00:10:40,335
We're expected to be cops,
uh, psychologists,

311
00:10:40,378 --> 00:10:42,859
social workers, teachers,
mediators.

312
00:10:42,903 --> 00:10:44,644
And they only train us
for one of those jobs.

313
00:10:44,687 --> 00:10:46,689
Gold truck. Two cars ahead.

314
00:10:46,733 --> 00:10:47,429
That's him.

315
00:10:49,300 --> 00:10:50,562
Control, 7-Adam-15.

316
00:10:50,606 --> 00:10:52,782
We have eyes on the
Amber Alert suspect vehicle.

317
00:10:52,826 --> 00:10:55,176
Heading west on Pico,
passing Westlake.

318
00:10:55,219 --> 00:10:58,222
7-Adam-19, inbound on
Olympic, passing Ardmore.

319
00:10:58,266 --> 00:11:00,703
7-Adam-07, coming west
from Wilshire and Rimpau --

320
00:11:00,747 --> 00:11:02,139
moving to intercept
from the front.

321
00:11:02,183 --> 00:11:04,315
- Air Three responding.
- Heading west from Bell Gardens.

322
00:11:04,359 --> 00:11:06,840
ETA to your location --
approximately six minutes.

323
00:11:06,883 --> 00:11:08,755
Can you parallel suspect
until I get eyes on?

324
00:11:08,798 --> 00:11:09,930
Affirmative.

325
00:11:09,973 --> 00:11:11,192
Parallel?

326
00:11:11,235 --> 00:11:12,802
Yeah, we follow on side streets
and alleyways.

327
00:11:15,152 --> 00:11:16,545
Oh, so he doesn't spot you
and run?

328
00:11:16,588 --> 00:11:18,025
Exactly. Last thing we want

329
00:11:18,068 --> 00:11:19,722
is him speeding through
traffic with a baby in the car,

330
00:11:19,766 --> 00:11:20,854
especially since there's no way

331
00:11:20,897 --> 00:11:22,246
he's got an infant car seat in there.

332
00:11:22,290 --> 00:11:23,639
No, we'll just wait
until we have enough units,

333
00:11:23,683 --> 00:11:24,814
and then we'll box him in.

334
00:11:24,858 --> 00:11:26,729
Intersection ahead.
We still have him?

335
00:11:26,773 --> 00:11:28,122
Yeah, he's about half a car length ahead,

336
00:11:28,165 --> 00:11:29,384
but he's speeding up.

337
00:11:29,427 --> 00:11:30,951
He might've seen us
before we made our turn.

338
00:11:32,779 --> 00:11:34,737
7-Adam-19, Maxwell and Pico.

339
00:11:34,781 --> 00:11:36,521
West of target --waiting for him to pass.

340
00:11:40,264 --> 00:11:42,702
- Suspect just went past.
- Speed -- 50 miles an hour.

341
00:11:42,745 --> 00:11:43,877
We'll move to parallel
on the north.

342
00:11:43,920 --> 00:11:45,095
Copy that.

343
00:11:45,139 --> 00:11:46,401
Why not just set up a roadblock?

344
00:11:46,444 --> 00:11:48,011
Roadblocks are considered a lethal measure.

345
00:11:48,055 --> 00:11:49,012
Didn't know that.

346
00:11:49,056 --> 00:11:50,187
Yeah, there's a strong chance

347
00:11:50,231 --> 00:11:51,972
a desperate driver will ram a roadblock.

348
00:11:52,015 --> 00:11:53,277
Clear!

349
00:11:53,321 --> 00:11:54,757
We don't use them unless we
have no other choice.

350
00:11:54,801 --> 00:11:56,063
- Come on, come on.
- Watch out, watch out!

351
00:11:57,717 --> 00:11:58,413
I can't see around the truck.

352
00:11:58,456 --> 00:11:59,631
Move it! I got it.

353
00:11:59,675 --> 00:12:00,807
- Move! Hey!
- I got it after this car.

354
00:12:00,850 --> 00:12:02,983
- Hold on. There we go.
- Got it.

355
00:12:05,420 --> 00:12:07,465
- Do you see him?
- No.

356
00:12:07,509 --> 00:12:09,816
Well, maybe -- maybe he turned
around when we got stuck.

357
00:12:09,859 --> 00:12:11,469
7-Adam-19, we've lost visual.

358
00:12:11,513 --> 00:12:12,775
You got eyes on him?

359
00:12:12,819 --> 00:12:14,734
- Negative.
- We haven't reacquired visual.

360
00:12:14,777 --> 00:12:16,692
Where the hell is that airship?

361
00:12:16,736 --> 00:12:18,825
Air Three is overhead.
Arriving on scene.

362
00:12:18,868 --> 00:12:20,652
What's the suspect's 20?

363
00:12:20,696 --> 00:12:22,654
We lost visual.
Pico, east of Maxwell.

364
00:12:22,698 --> 00:12:24,874
It's possible he turned off
and headed either north or south.

365
00:12:24,918 --> 00:12:26,528
Copy that. We're gonna orbit.

366
00:12:31,576 --> 00:12:33,100
Contact.

367
00:12:33,143 --> 00:12:34,928
Suspect vehicle now heading
north on Livingston.

368
00:12:34,971 --> 00:12:36,625
Repeat, north on Livingston.

369
00:12:36,668 --> 00:12:38,322
Copy. On our way.

370
00:12:38,366 --> 00:12:40,672
Speed is approximately 65.

371
00:12:40,716 --> 00:12:41,717
Looks like he's heading
for the freeway.

372
00:12:46,635 --> 00:12:47,723
Hold on.

373
00:12:47,767 --> 00:12:49,420
Suspect just sideswiped
another vehicle.

374
00:12:49,464 --> 00:12:51,074
He's lost control.

375
00:12:53,294 --> 00:12:54,817
Tell me that wasn't our guy.

376
00:12:54,861 --> 00:12:56,427
<i>He just TC'd into
a telephone pole.</i>

377
00:12:56,471 --> 00:12:58,429
Can you see inside the truck?

378
00:12:58,473 --> 00:12:59,691
<i>Negative.</i>

379
00:13:11,616 --> 00:13:12,661
Hands! Police!

380
00:13:15,272 --> 00:13:16,926
Show me your hands!

381
00:13:16,970 --> 00:13:18,145
Where is your daughter?

382
00:13:18,188 --> 00:13:19,668
What?

383
00:13:19,711 --> 00:13:21,452
Keep your hands
where we can see them.

384
00:13:25,674 --> 00:13:27,110
No kid. There's no kid in here!

385
00:13:27,154 --> 00:13:28,285
There's no kid!

386
00:13:28,329 --> 00:13:29,678
Your baby, where is she?

387
00:13:29,721 --> 00:13:31,158
At the hospital with her mom.

388
00:13:31,201 --> 00:13:32,246
Then why did you run?

389
00:13:32,289 --> 00:13:33,813
Gun and drugs.

390
00:13:36,163 --> 00:13:37,773
If he doesn't have
the baby, who does?

391
00:13:44,084 --> 00:13:45,476
Never thought
I'd be disappointed

392
00:13:45,520 --> 00:13:47,827
a meth-head <i>wasn't
taking care of a newborn.</i>

393
00:13:47,870 --> 00:13:49,132
But I guess there's still
plenty of time

394
00:13:49,176 --> 00:13:50,960
for him to mess up
this kid's childhood,

395
00:13:51,004 --> 00:13:52,135
once we get her back.

396
00:13:53,310 --> 00:13:54,355
<i>If</i> we get her back.

397
00:13:56,400 --> 00:13:58,750
You know, whenever you need
Halloween costumes

398
00:13:58,794 --> 00:14:00,230
for Lopez Jr.,

399
00:14:00,274 --> 00:14:02,711
my mom has dozens in storage.

400
00:14:02,754 --> 00:14:05,583
I'm talking cop uniforms
for every age.

401
00:14:05,627 --> 00:14:07,324
You never really wanted
to be anything else?

402
00:14:09,109 --> 00:14:11,459
Astronaut? Ninja?

403
00:14:11,502 --> 00:14:12,852
Ninja astronaut?

404
00:14:12,895 --> 00:14:15,637
I mean, that'd be cool,
but... mnh-mnh.

405
00:14:15,680 --> 00:14:16,681
No.

406
00:14:16,725 --> 00:14:18,945
I guess I just
wanted to be my dad.

407
00:14:18,988 --> 00:14:21,077
It was like my way of
feeling close to him

408
00:14:21,121 --> 00:14:22,122
when he wasn't around.

409
00:14:22,165 --> 00:14:24,298
Was that a lot? Yeah.

410
00:14:24,341 --> 00:14:26,866
I mean, he was a detective
when I was born,

411
00:14:26,909 --> 00:14:29,259
trying to make a name
for himself.

412
00:14:29,303 --> 00:14:31,087
Lot of long hours.

413
00:14:31,131 --> 00:14:32,306
But you were close.

414
00:14:32,349 --> 00:14:33,960
Yeah, eventually.

415
00:14:34,003 --> 00:14:36,919
Mom was kind of on her own
until I was 12.

416
00:14:36,963 --> 00:14:39,226
And that's when he moved up,
got more stable hours.

417
00:14:39,269 --> 00:14:40,967
Mm.

418
00:14:41,010 --> 00:14:44,144
I mean, I always loved him --

419
00:14:44,187 --> 00:14:46,929
don't get me wrong --
even when he wasn't around.

420
00:14:46,973 --> 00:14:50,063
I have a lot of
great memories, you know?

421
00:14:50,106 --> 00:14:51,629
Of course.

422
00:14:51,673 --> 00:14:54,458
You know, you and Wesley are
going to be awesome parents.

423
00:14:54,502 --> 00:14:56,591
I know.

424
00:14:56,634 --> 00:14:58,201
It's just...

425
00:14:58,245 --> 00:15:00,247
We both get so wrapped up
in our cases,

426
00:15:00,290 --> 00:15:03,380
we barely make time
to have dinner together.

427
00:15:03,424 --> 00:15:05,121
How are we supposed to make time for a kid?

428
00:15:05,165 --> 00:15:08,298
Wesley is loaded.
You get yourself a nanny.

429
00:15:08,342 --> 00:15:09,734
Or three.

430
00:15:09,778 --> 00:15:11,040
So a stranger
can raise my child?

431
00:15:11,084 --> 00:15:12,302
I mean, it won't be a stranger

432
00:15:12,346 --> 00:15:14,870
when you get to know them,
you know?

433
00:15:14,914 --> 00:15:17,046
Look, you are not
the first detective

434
00:15:17,090 --> 00:15:19,179
to have to balance work
with a kid.

435
00:15:19,222 --> 00:15:20,571
Talk to Harper
about how she did it.

436
00:15:22,182 --> 00:15:25,098
<i>Harper, can you ten-three
to a backup channel?</i>

437
00:15:26,838 --> 00:15:29,406
Sure, go to 11.
Don't record this.

438
00:15:33,497 --> 00:15:35,847
I need you to give
me the reals on something.

439
00:15:35,891 --> 00:15:37,153
How difficult was it
to go back to work

440
00:15:37,197 --> 00:15:38,589
after Lila was born?

441
00:15:39,895 --> 00:15:41,157
Honestly, I barely remember.

442
00:15:41,201 --> 00:15:42,942
I almost died
giving birth, so...

443
00:15:44,073 --> 00:15:46,902
But, uh, that's -- that's not
gonna happen to you.

444
00:15:46,946 --> 00:15:51,037
G-Giving birth can be
a wonderful experience,

445
00:15:51,080 --> 00:15:53,343
I've been told.

446
00:15:53,387 --> 00:15:54,562
Definitely get the epidural.

447
00:15:54,605 --> 00:15:56,912
Don't worry. I'm not a lunatic.

448
00:15:56,956 --> 00:15:59,219
I'm thinking of scheduling
a C, but I'm worried

449
00:15:59,262 --> 00:16:00,611
that the stitches and everything

450
00:16:00,655 --> 00:16:03,136
will keep me off work even longer.

451
00:16:03,179 --> 00:16:05,007
I worried about the same
thing, but you know what?

452
00:16:05,051 --> 00:16:06,269
I got stitches anyway --

453
00:16:06,313 --> 00:16:08,097
just not in my stomach.

454
00:16:08,141 --> 00:16:09,751
Okay. Change us back
to channel one.

455
00:16:09,794 --> 00:16:11,666
Wh-- I-I-- I think I want to hear this.

456
00:16:13,059 --> 00:16:14,799
Tell me the truth --

457
00:16:14,843 --> 00:16:16,671
Am I gonna poop myself?

458
00:16:16,714 --> 00:16:18,368
And I'm out.

459
00:16:18,412 --> 00:16:19,500
Wow.

460
00:16:20,675 --> 00:16:22,242
I wish I could say no.

461
00:16:22,285 --> 00:16:24,157
Why can't we just do
that twilight sleep thing

462
00:16:24,200 --> 00:16:25,593
they did back in the '50s?

463
00:16:25,636 --> 00:16:27,029
I asked.

464
00:16:27,073 --> 00:16:29,858
Apparently it is
"grossly unethical."

465
00:16:29,901 --> 00:16:32,556
<i>Detectives, are you done?</i>

466
00:16:32,600 --> 00:16:33,557
Yes, sir.

467
00:16:38,649 --> 00:16:41,739
We must seem callous,
joking while a kid is missing.

468
00:16:41,783 --> 00:16:43,045
No, I get it. I'm sure it's hard

469
00:16:43,089 --> 00:16:45,091
to work these kinds of cases.

470
00:16:45,134 --> 00:16:46,831
Calls involving kids are the worst.

471
00:16:46,875 --> 00:16:48,181
You can't help but think,
what if they were mine?

472
00:16:48,224 --> 00:16:49,269
Mm.

473
00:16:49,312 --> 00:16:50,313
Yeah, I don't have kids,

474
00:16:50,357 --> 00:16:52,359
but I feel the same way

475
00:16:52,402 --> 00:16:54,578
every time another Black kid
gets shot by police.

476
00:16:59,018 --> 00:17:01,585
Oh. Hospital sent the
video of the kidnapping.

477
00:17:03,326 --> 00:17:04,719
You can't see her face.

478
00:17:06,503 --> 00:17:07,896
That is just terrifying.

479
00:17:07,939 --> 00:17:09,898
A stranger snatching your baby

480
00:17:09,941 --> 00:17:11,073
when you're not thereto protect them.

481
00:17:11,117 --> 00:17:12,379
Don't worry.

482
00:17:12,422 --> 00:17:14,076
I will personally
stand watch over your kid

483
00:17:14,120 --> 00:17:15,208
until you leave the hospital.

484
00:17:15,251 --> 00:17:16,774
You better.

485
00:17:16,818 --> 00:17:18,428
Do they have an ID
on the kidnapper?

486
00:17:18,472 --> 00:17:19,342
Not yet.

487
00:17:19,386 --> 00:17:20,735
Listen to me.

488
00:17:20,778 --> 00:17:23,694
We're gonna find her, alright?

489
00:17:23,738 --> 00:17:25,174
And that baby's gonna be fine.

490
00:17:25,218 --> 00:17:26,480
You'll see.

491
00:17:31,876 --> 00:17:33,269
We don't have time for this.

492
00:17:33,313 --> 00:17:35,402
Every minute we waste
waiting for an ID on this woman

493
00:17:35,445 --> 00:17:36,925
is a minute she could
be hurting this kid --

494
00:17:36,968 --> 00:17:38,274
or worse.

495
00:17:38,318 --> 00:17:39,275
Look, you need to
get your head right

496
00:17:39,319 --> 00:17:40,233
in case this goes bad.

497
00:17:40,276 --> 00:17:42,104
I'm squared away.

498
00:17:42,148 --> 00:17:45,064
The fact that you just said that
means you're not.

499
00:17:46,369 --> 00:17:48,067
Look, you've been lucky
on the job so far.

500
00:17:49,590 --> 00:17:51,548
No. Alright.

501
00:17:51,592 --> 00:17:54,508
I'm sorry. That --
That came out wrong.

502
00:17:54,551 --> 00:17:55,900
You've been through Hell --

503
00:17:55,944 --> 00:17:58,512
stuff that would've broken
a lot of veteran cops.

504
00:17:58,555 --> 00:18:01,080
But a dead kid is different.

505
00:18:01,123 --> 00:18:04,039
A dead kid changes you forever.

506
00:18:06,824 --> 00:18:09,218
I really hope our last shift together

507
00:18:09,262 --> 00:18:10,524
doesn't end with that.

508
00:18:10,567 --> 00:18:13,222
Yeah. Me too.

509
00:18:14,571 --> 00:18:16,530
Okay, so what's next
on your list?

510
00:18:19,620 --> 00:18:23,276
Okay.

511
00:18:23,319 --> 00:18:24,668
"Surround yourself with people

512
00:18:24,712 --> 00:18:27,149
who support, value,
and energize you,"

513
00:18:27,193 --> 00:18:30,239
which... may have to wait until later.

514
00:18:30,283 --> 00:18:32,850
Then, uh, "Reflect on
the lessons learned --

515
00:18:32,894 --> 00:18:36,463
both the good and the bad
--and express gratitude."

516
00:18:37,812 --> 00:18:39,944
Okay.

517
00:18:39,988 --> 00:18:42,556
So, what have I taught you
that you're grateful for?

518
00:18:42,599 --> 00:18:44,601
Um... hmm.

519
00:18:46,429 --> 00:18:49,258
Not to second-guess myself.

520
00:18:49,302 --> 00:18:51,304
Yeah, early on,

521
