00:30:05,673 --> 00:30:07,283
Reminded me of my ex-wife.

775
00:30:07,327 --> 00:30:08,937
Uh, yes, sir. Please call us

776
00:30:08,981 --> 00:30:10,852
if you remember
anything else.
Okay.

777
00:30:10,896 --> 00:30:13,159
Control, 7-Adam-19, I got
the vehicle, unoccupied.

778
00:30:13,202 --> 00:30:15,161
Witness says the suspect
here less than five minutes ago.

779
00:30:15,204 --> 00:30:16,336
She's on foot.

780
00:30:16,379 --> 00:30:17,685
We need backup and an airship

781
00:30:17,728 --> 00:30:18,773
to secure a 10-block radius

782
00:30:18,817 --> 00:30:19,992
for a grid search.

783
00:30:22,951 --> 00:30:24,039
I don't like this.

784
00:30:24,083 --> 00:30:25,084
She wouldn't have abandoned
the car

785
00:30:25,127 --> 00:30:26,607
unless she stopped for a reason.

786
00:30:26,650 --> 00:30:28,261
Odds are it won't be a good one.

787
00:30:28,304 --> 00:30:29,915
We gotta find her fast.

788
00:30:33,788 --> 00:30:35,790
This is crazy.

789
00:30:35,834 --> 00:30:37,183
There's no way we find her
and the baby in time.

790
00:30:37,226 --> 00:30:39,315
We've got multiple units
and an airship searching.

791
00:30:39,359 --> 00:30:40,273
We will find them.

792
00:30:40,316 --> 00:30:41,752
How? They could be anywhere.

793
00:30:41,796 --> 00:30:43,885
No. On foot with a newborn and
a five-minute head start,

794
00:30:43,929 --> 00:30:45,582
she's definitely within our grid.

795
00:30:45,626 --> 00:30:47,019
Someone will have seen her.

796
00:30:47,062 --> 00:30:50,457
Just... pray we find her
before she does something rash.

797
00:30:59,770 --> 00:31:00,815
Up on the right.

798
00:31:05,080 --> 00:31:07,126
Not her.

799
00:31:10,303 --> 00:31:11,478
Can I make a suggestion?

800
00:31:11,521 --> 00:31:12,914
Of course.

801
00:31:12,958 --> 00:31:14,829
Would it be helpful to have
Rita's husband

802
00:31:14,873 --> 00:31:18,050
brought down here
for -- for when she's found?

803
00:31:18,093 --> 00:31:19,573
That could be dangerous.

804
00:31:19,616 --> 00:31:21,575
We don't know what the
situation was like at the house,

805
00:31:21,618 --> 00:31:24,012
and even if the baby's death
truly was accidental,

806
00:31:24,056 --> 00:31:25,840
there could have been
marital issues

807
00:31:25,884 --> 00:31:27,494
that added to Rita's PPD.

808
00:31:27,537 --> 00:31:29,191
We'd be introducing a wildcard

809
00:31:29,235 --> 00:31:30,540
to an already tenuous situation.

810
00:31:30,584 --> 00:31:32,151
Wait, so it's all on you?

811
00:31:32,194 --> 00:31:34,370
I mean, no matter what you find
when you get to her,

812
00:31:34,414 --> 00:31:35,502
you have to be ready to
deal with it?

813
00:31:35,545 --> 00:31:38,157
What -- What if you make
a mistake?

814
00:31:38,200 --> 00:31:39,985
We have to live with it.

815
00:31:40,028 --> 00:31:42,596
If we can.

816
00:31:42,639 --> 00:31:45,207
<i>All units, Air Three has
eyes on the suspect.</i>

817
00:31:45,251 --> 00:31:46,295
Fourth Street Bridge.

818
00:31:46,339 --> 00:31:49,037
Repeat -- Fourth Street Bridge.

819
00:31:49,081 --> 00:31:51,257
She has the baby.
She's standing at the railing.

820
00:31:51,300 --> 00:31:53,824
Possible jumper.
Repeat, possible jumper.

821
00:31:53,868 --> 00:31:55,130
Here we go.

822
00:31:55,174 --> 00:31:57,263
Control, advise Fire we have
a possible jumper

823
00:31:57,306 --> 00:31:58,394
on Fourth Street Bridge.

824
00:31:58,438 --> 00:31:59,700
See if they have a crash pad available.

825
00:31:59,743 --> 00:32:03,051
We'll also need RA
and backup units, Code 2 high.

826
00:32:17,413 --> 00:32:19,285
Maybe I should stay back.

827
00:32:19,328 --> 00:32:20,677
Uh, it's up to you,

828
00:32:20,721 --> 00:32:22,070
but a friendly face
not in uniform

829
00:32:22,114 --> 00:32:23,854
might actually calm
the situation.

830
00:32:23,898 --> 00:32:25,291
How do you want to play this?

831
00:32:25,334 --> 00:32:26,031
You go talk to her.

832
00:32:26,074 --> 00:32:27,336
You sure?

833
00:32:27,380 --> 00:32:28,947
Yeah, I'll step in if I need to.

834
00:32:31,645 --> 00:32:34,561
W-Why -- Why Nolan?

835
00:32:34,604 --> 00:32:38,217
He has a way of connecting with
people in crisis situations.

836
00:32:38,260 --> 00:32:40,610
Hi, Rita.

837
00:32:40,654 --> 00:32:41,698
I'm John.

838
00:32:42,743 --> 00:32:44,266
How do you know my name?

839
00:32:44,310 --> 00:32:45,659
Uh, Ethan told me.

840
00:32:45,702 --> 00:32:48,053
He's very worried about you.

841
00:32:48,096 --> 00:32:50,011
I'm fine.

842
00:32:50,055 --> 00:32:51,970
Who's that you got there?

843
00:32:52,013 --> 00:32:53,275
Casey.

844
00:32:53,319 --> 00:32:54,581
This is Casey.

845
00:32:54,624 --> 00:32:56,017
Oh.

846
00:32:56,061 --> 00:32:57,714
Casey looks a little bit cold.

847
00:32:57,758 --> 00:32:59,673
Why don't we bring her inside,
off the bridge?

848
00:32:59,716 --> 00:33:00,587
No.

849
00:33:00,630 --> 00:33:03,068
She's fine with her mama.

850
00:33:03,111 --> 00:33:05,157
Do you mind if I just make sure?

851
00:33:05,200 --> 00:33:06,375
Stay back.

852
00:33:06,419 --> 00:33:07,420
Okay, yeah. I'll stay back.

853
00:33:07,463 --> 00:33:08,769
We -- We can just talk.

854
00:33:17,386 --> 00:33:18,170
How's she doing?

855
00:33:18,213 --> 00:33:20,302
Uh, it's touch and go.

856
00:33:20,346 --> 00:33:22,000
- What do you need?
- Keep them back.

857
00:33:22,043 --> 00:33:23,740
We don't want to spook her.

858
00:33:23,784 --> 00:33:25,742
-Okay.
No, I know it can
feel isolating,

859
00:33:25,786 --> 00:33:27,440
being a parent to a newborn...

860
00:33:27,483 --> 00:33:28,571
She's not looking at the baby.

861
00:33:28,615 --> 00:33:30,312
...so much to learn.

862
00:33:30,356 --> 00:33:32,010
You never feel like
what you're doing...

863
00:33:32,053 --> 00:33:33,576
She's trying to convince herself

864
00:33:33,620 --> 00:33:35,317
that it's her baby
she's holding.

865
00:33:35,361 --> 00:33:37,928
Yeah. Deep down inside,
she knows it's not.

866
00:33:37,972 --> 00:33:40,018
What happens when
she figures out the truth?

867
00:33:40,061 --> 00:33:41,671
It's hard to say for sure.

868
00:33:41,715 --> 00:33:43,195
It could break the spell or it
could send her over the edge,

869
00:33:43,238 --> 00:33:44,544
literally.

870
00:33:44,587 --> 00:33:46,328
Control, what's the ETA on Fire?

871
00:33:46,372 --> 00:33:47,590
<i>Three minutes.</i>

872
00:33:47,634 --> 00:33:49,157
Might as well be three hours.

873
00:33:49,201 --> 00:33:51,551
Are you thirsty, Rita?

874
00:33:51,594 --> 00:33:52,247
I can get you some water.

875
00:33:52,291 --> 00:33:53,814
Nolan.

876
00:33:53,857 --> 00:33:55,294
Can I talk to her?

877
00:33:55,337 --> 00:33:56,469
Hey, Rita, I'm gonna
introduce you

878
00:33:56,512 --> 00:33:57,992
to my friend, Angela, okay?

879
00:33:58,036 --> 00:33:59,472
Okay.

880
00:33:59,515 --> 00:34:00,995
Hi, Rita.

881
00:34:01,039 --> 00:34:03,084
I'm here to help.

882
00:34:03,128 --> 00:34:04,129
Is this Casey?

883
00:34:05,478 --> 00:34:07,045
Yes.

884
00:34:07,088 --> 00:34:08,524
I love that name.

885
00:34:08,568 --> 00:34:12,311
My fiancé and I can't agree
on a name for our baby.

886
00:34:12,354 --> 00:34:13,921
How did you choose?

887
00:34:13,964 --> 00:34:16,097
I don't know.

888
00:34:16,141 --> 00:34:18,230
When she was born, she just
looked like a Casey.

889
00:34:21,146 --> 00:34:22,756
How far along are you?

890
00:34:22,799 --> 00:34:24,497
14 weeks.

891
00:34:24,540 --> 00:34:27,108
I'm already scared
about giving birth.

892
00:34:27,152 --> 00:34:28,283
The pain.

893
00:34:28,327 --> 00:34:30,590
Don't worry about the pain.

894
00:34:30,633 --> 00:34:34,289
Once they put your baby
in your arms

895
00:34:34,333 --> 00:34:37,727
and you look down into
those beautiful eyes,

896
00:34:37,771 --> 00:34:39,555
it was all worth it.

897
00:34:39,599 --> 00:34:43,124
I heard all newborns
have blue eyes.

898
00:34:43,168 --> 00:34:44,647
Not Casey.

899
00:34:44,691 --> 00:34:48,042
Dark brown,
right from the start.

900
00:34:48,086 --> 00:34:50,784
The most amazing head of hair.

901
00:34:50,827 --> 00:34:51,654
I hope if I have a daughter,

902
00:34:51,698 --> 00:34:53,439
she's born with hair.

903
00:34:53,482 --> 00:34:56,442
My cousin's little girl,
she was bald

904
00:34:56,485 --> 00:34:58,487
for like the first 18 months.

905
00:34:58,531 --> 00:35:00,141
Everyone thought she was a boy.

906
00:35:00,185 --> 00:35:01,403
I love putting

907
00:35:01,447 --> 00:35:03,884
Casey's hair in little pigtails.

908
00:35:03,927 --> 00:35:07,757
She always fights me,
but she looks so cute.

909
00:35:07,801 --> 00:35:12,153
Rita, can you do something
for me?

910
00:35:12,197 --> 00:35:13,763
Can you look at Casey?

911
00:35:13,807 --> 00:35:15,896
Just look in those pretty,
brown eyes.

912
00:35:18,420 --> 00:35:19,421
No.

913
00:35:19,465 --> 00:35:20,596
Please, Rita.

914
00:35:20,640 --> 00:35:22,337
I need you to look in her eyes.

915
00:35:32,391 --> 00:35:35,959
It's not Casey, is it?

916
00:35:36,003 --> 00:35:40,138
No.

917
00:35:40,181 --> 00:35:42,792
Here. I got her.

918
00:35:42,836 --> 00:35:45,491
I'll get her back to
her mother, okay?

919
00:35:49,103 --> 00:35:51,453
Tell her I'm sorry.

920
00:35:53,673 --> 00:35:55,065
Thank you, Rita.

921
00:35:55,109 --> 00:35:57,242
That was a very brave thing you did,

922
00:35:57,285 --> 00:35:59,287
and now I need you to come with me, okay?

923
00:36:00,593 --> 00:36:02,899
My baby died.

924
00:36:02,943 --> 00:36:04,336
I know.

925
00:36:04,379 --> 00:36:05,511
I'm so sorry.

926
00:36:07,774 --> 00:36:11,647
Come on. Come on.

927
00:36:31,754 --> 00:36:33,669
Well, thank you for today.

928
00:36:33,713 --> 00:36:35,976
This is an experience
I will not forget.

929
00:36:36,019 --> 00:36:38,108
Well, we should schedule

930
00:36:38,152 --> 00:36:40,067
another one of these little ride alongs

931
00:36:40,110 --> 00:36:41,895
so that we can continue the conversation.

932
00:36:41,938 --> 00:36:43,505
Oh, that won't be necessary.

933
00:36:44,680 --> 00:36:47,205
The book's already written,
isn't it?

934
00:36:47,248 --> 00:36:49,119
I sent it to my publisher
last week.

935
00:36:49,163 --> 00:36:50,599
Mm. What?

936
00:36:50,643 --> 00:36:52,122
Then what was today about, then?

937
00:36:52,166 --> 00:36:54,168
Just an anecdote
for the book tour?

938
00:36:54,212 --> 00:36:56,562
No, I didn't know the day was
gonna end up the way it did.

939
00:36:56,605 --> 00:36:58,520
But how do you write a book
about policing

940
00:36:58,564 --> 00:36:59,608
without having seen it up close?

941
00:36:59,652 --> 00:37:01,610
Oh, I have seen it. Believe me.

942
00:37:01,654 --> 00:37:03,133
Today may have been
my first ride along,

943
00:37:03,177 --> 00:37:04,222
but it was not my first time

944
00:37:04,265 --> 00:37:05,788
sitting in the back seat
of a cop car.

945
00:37:05,832 --> 00:37:08,138
I see, but if you're going to
fix an engine,

946
00:37:08,182 --> 00:37:09,792
don't you think it would be
helpful to look under the hood?

947
00:37:09,836 --> 00:37:12,012
That is a flawed analogy,
Officer Nolan,

948
00:37:12,055 --> 00:37:13,492
because a car is not
actively trying to

949
00:37:13,535 --> 00:37:14,710
keep you from fixing it.

950
00:37:16,103 --> 00:37:17,452
Uh, excuse me.

951
00:37:19,759 --> 00:37:22,762
Look, I get that the path
to real change

952
00:37:22,805 --> 00:37:24,764
seems almost impossible.

953
00:37:24,807 --> 00:37:27,723
I mean, police departments are
pros at circling the wagons

954
00:37:27,767 --> 00:37:30,291
when public opinion
turns against them.

955
00:37:30,335 --> 00:37:33,076
But I promise you,

956
00:37:33,120 --> 00:37:35,427
the only way
things really will change

957
00:37:35,470 --> 00:37:37,820
is if cops get on board.

958
00:37:37,864 --> 00:37:39,257
I agree.

959
00:37:39,300 --> 00:37:41,694
But cops only act when activists
make so much noise,

960
00:37:41,737 --> 00:37:43,304
they cannot be ignored.

961
00:37:43,348 --> 00:37:44,827
Like in Camden.

962
00:37:44,871 --> 00:37:47,177
Look, you're talking to
two police officers

963
00:37:47,221 --> 00:37:48,831
who would like to
see things change,

964
00:37:48,875 --> 00:37:51,834
and we're not the only ones at
the station that feels this way.

965
00:37:51,878 --> 00:37:55,316
I just think that...
uh, maybe you could benefit

966
00:37:55,360 --> 00:37:57,753
from some of our insights.

967
00:38:01,931 --> 00:38:02,802
Alright.

968
00:38:04,020 --> 00:38:05,674
You sold me.

969
00:38:05,718 --> 00:38:07,676
Great. I'll tell Sergeant Grey.

970
00:38:07,720 --> 00:38:09,243
I'm sure he'd love to
be part of the conversation.

971
00:38:09,287 --> 00:38:10,853
Oh, thank you.

972
00:38:10,897 --> 00:38:13,726
And thank you both for
the ride along.

973
00:38:13,769 --> 00:38:15,336
I will see you in class.

974
00:38:15,380 --> 00:38:16,642
Looking forward.

975
00:38:19,732 --> 00:38:22,604
I think that went well,
all things considered.

976
00:38:22,648 --> 00:38:24,780
Oh, yeah. No, she's definitely
gonna give you an "A."

977
00:38:24,824 --> 00:38:26,608
- You think?
- No.

978
00:38:26,652 --> 00:38:28,349
She is gonna make you earn it
in class,

979
00:38:28,393 --> 00:38:29,698
like the rest of her students.

980
00:38:29,742 --> 00:38:31,221
Fair enough. Yeah.

981
00:38:31,265 --> 00:38:32,701
You have any plans for
the rest of the night?

982
00:38:32,745 --> 00:38:34,921
Hugging my daughter
until she is sick of it

983
00:38:34,964 --> 00:38:36,923
and then hugging her some more.
Sounds nice.

984
00:38:36,966 --> 00:38:37,924
Nolan.

985
00:38:39,534 --> 00:38:41,101
- I'll see you tomorrow.
- Alright.

986
00:38:41,144 --> 00:38:42,929
Sir. Well?

987
00:38:42,972 --> 00:38:44,539
How'd it go with Professor Ryan?

988
00:38:44,583 --> 00:38:46,149
Good, I think.

989
00:38:46,193 --> 00:38:48,021
She's gonna be calling you to
talk about, uh, police reform --

990
00:38:48,064 --> 00:38:49,283
for her book.

991
00:38:51,416 --> 00:38:53,766
You point her my way to get back
at me for the ride along?

992
00:38:53,809 --> 00:38:54,810
No, sir. No.

993
00:38:54,854 --> 00:38:55,811
I just know
how committed you are

994
00:38:55,855 --> 00:38:57,900
to making things better.

995
00:38:57,944 --> 00:39:00,294
Even if it does mean having to
admit you're wrong to do it.

996
00:39:00,338 --> 00:39:02,383
Oh. Uh, I'm sorry?

997
00:39:03,515 --> 00:39:05,691
When was I ever wrong?

998
00:39:05,734 --> 00:39:08,998
Well, nothing comes to
mind off hand.

999
00:39:09,042 --> 00:39:11,784
I guess there was that one time
you said if I succeeded,

1000
00:39:11,827 --> 00:39:14,352
your house would be
"flooded with middle-aged losers

1001
00:39:14,395 --> 00:39:18,530
looking for an 'Eat Pray Love'
path to reinvention."

1002
00:39:18,573 --> 00:39:20,836
I wrote it down.

1003
00:39:20,880 --> 00:39:23,839
You haven't succeeded yet,
Officer Nolan.

1004
00:39:23,883 --> 00:39:26,233
Yes, sir.

1005
00:39:26,276 --> 00:39:26,973
Good night, sir.

1006
00:39:27,016 --> 00:39:29,410
Good night.

1007
00:39:29,454 --> 00:39:31,412
Can't wait to get out
of this uniform.

1008
00:39:31,456 --> 00:39:32,935
Hey, thanks again for
riding with me.

1009
00:39:32,979 --> 00:39:34,154
Are you kidding me?

1010
00:39:34,197 --> 00:39:35,895
I wouldn't have missed it
for the world.

1011
00:39:35,938 --> 00:39:38,376
And now it's end of shift,

1012
00:39:38,419 --> 00:39:40,813
and you are no longer a rookie.

1013
00:39:42,336 --> 00:39:43,946
How does it feel?

1014
00:39:43,990 --> 00:39:45,992
Unreal.

1015
00:39:46,035 --> 00:39:48,124
I mean, everything in my life
has been geared towards

1016
00:39:48,168 --> 00:39:52,607
getting me to this moment,
and... now it's here.

1017
00:39:52,651 --> 00:39:54,392
Kinda can't believe it,
to be honest.

1018
00:39:54,435 --> 00:39:57,525
Well, congratulations.

1019
00:39:57,569 --> 00:39:59,222
You earned it.

1020
00:39:59,266 --> 00:40:00,485
♪ I couldn't see the forest
for the trees ♪

1021
00:40:00,528 --> 00:40:03,444
♪ Too many empties on the side

1022
00:40:03,488 --> 00:40:05,925
♪ But I kept trading all
my cigarettes for sunsets ♪

1023
00:40:05,968 --> 00:40:06,969
♪ Now I'm getting richer
all the time ♪

1024
00:40:07,013 --> 00:40:08,841
We did it.

1025
00:40:08,884 --> 00:40:10,712
No. <i>You</i> did it.

1026
00:40:13,411 --> 00:40:14,934
What's this?

1027
00:40:14,977 --> 00:40:17,545
It's a copy of
your final evaluation.

1028
00:40:17,589 --> 00:40:19,460
I wrote it
before our shift today.

1029
00:40:19,504 --> 00:40:21,854
Like Plain Clothes Day.

1030
00:40:21,897 --> 00:40:23,812
Only this time,
I didn't have to rewrite it.

1031
00:40:23,856 --> 00:40:25,466
Mm.

1032
00:40:25,510 --> 00:40:26,772
♪ I'll be young before I die

1033
00:40:26,815 --> 00:40:28,469
"Officer Chen impressed me

1034
00:40:28,513 --> 00:40:30,471
with every decision she made
today.

